SIMPLE: hatch
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hatch
<hw>Hatch</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧ch)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hatched</conjf> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧cht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Hatching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>hacher</ets> to chop, hack. See <er>Hash</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To cross with lines in a peculiar manner in drawing and engraving.
See <er>Hatching</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shall win this sword, silvered and <qex>hatched</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those <qex>hatching</qex> strokes of the pencil.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cross; to spot; to stain; to steep.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His weapon <qex>hatched</qex> in blood.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hatch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hatch
<hw>Hatch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>hacchen</ets>,
<ets>hetchen</ets>; akin to G. <ets>hecken</ets>, Dan. <ets>hekke</ets>;
cf. MHG. <ets>hagen</ets> bull; perh. akin to E. <ets>hatch</ets> a half
door, and originally meaning, to produce under a hatch. ⟦root⟧12.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To produce, as young, from an egg or eggs by
incubation, or by artificial heat; to produce young from (eggs); <as>as,
the young when <ex>hatched</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Paley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As the partridge sitteth on eggs, and <qex>hatcheth</qex> them
not.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. xvii. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For the hens do not sit upon the eggs; but by keeping them in a
certain equal heat they [the husbandmen] bring life into them and
<qex>hatch</qex> them.</q> <rj><qau>Robynson (More's
Utopia).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To contrive or plot; to form by meditation, and
bring into being; to originate and produce; to concoct; <as>as, to
<ex>hatch</ex> mischief; to <ex>hatch</ex> heresy.</as></def>
<rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fancies <qex>hatched</qex>⟦br⟧
In silken-folded idleness.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hatch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hatch
<hw>Hatch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To produce young; -- said of eggs;
to come forth from the egg; -- said of the young of birds, fishes,
insects, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hatch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hatch
<hw>Hatch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
hatching.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Development; disclosure; discovery.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The chickens produced at once or by one incubation;
a brood.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hatch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Hatch
<hw>Hatch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>hacche</ets>, AS.
<ets>h⟦ae⟧c</ets>, cf. <ets>haca</ets> the bar of a door, D.
<ets>hek</ets> gate, Sw. <ets>h⟦aum⟧ck</ets> coop, rack, Dan.
<ets>hekke</ets> manger, rack. Prob. akin to E. <ets>hook</ets>, and
first used of something made of pieces fastened together. Cf.
<er>Heck</er>, <er>Hack</er> a frame.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A door
with an opening over it; a half door, sometimes set with spikes on the
upper edge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In at the window, or else o'er the <qex>hatch</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A frame or weir in a river, for catching
fish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A flood gate; a sluice gate.</def>
<rj><au>Ainsworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A bedstead.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir
W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An opening in the deck of a vessel or floor of a
warehouse which serves as a passageway or hoistway; a hatchway; also; a
cover or door, or one of the covers used in closing such an
opening.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>An opening into, or in search
of, a mine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Booby hatch</b></col>, <col><b>Buttery
hatch</b></col>, <col><b>Companion hatch</b></col>, etc.</mcol> <cd>See
under <er>Booby</er>, <er>Buttery</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>To batten
down the hatches</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to lay tarpaulins
over them, and secure them with battens.</cd> -- <col><b>To be under
hatches</b></col>, <cd>to be confined below in a vessel; to be under
arrest, or in slavery, distress, etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hatch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Hatch
<hw>Hatch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To close with a hatch or
hatches.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T were not amiss to keep our door <qex>hatched</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hatch-boat</ent>⟦br⟧
